{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602036/1937101701/0723.xml":{"full_text":"Mr\u20141..\nSTAMPS\nAuthorized by the Post Office Department for reproduction,\nthe design for the Virgin Islands territorial stamp is shojvn\nabove. It represents Charlotte Amalie Harbor. The release\ndate is Wednesday, December 15. First-day covers should be\nsent to the Charlotte Amalie postmaster not later than\nDecember 1.\nBY JAMES WALDO FAWCETT.\nActing Third Assistant Postmaster\nGeneral Roy M. North will attend the\nThird American Philatelic Congress,\nHotel La Salle, Chicago. Friday to\nSunday, October 29 to 31. inclusive.\nHe will be one of the principal speak\ners at the banquet on Saturday eve\nning, October 30.\nJoseph Josselson, 1400 Grand Con\ncourse. New York City, desires to cor\nrespond with collectors interested to\njoin a King George V stamp club.\nHe specializes in issues showing por\ntraits of the late sovereign and would\nbe glad to hear from other philatelists\nwho have the same preference.\nKent Stiles is the latest philatelic\nbiographer of President Roosevelt.\nHis feature story on \"The Nation\u2019s\nNo. 1 Stamp Collector\" appeared in\nthe New York Times Sunday Mag\nazine, September 26.\nC. Robert Kay. philatelic editor of\nthe Associated Press, wires from New\nYork: \"The decline of prices on the\nNew York Stock Exchange has had\nan adverse effect on the stamp trade.\n\"Well-to-do collectors, after suffer\nlng actual or paper losses on stock\ntransactions, often stop buying stamps\nuntil their gloom is dispelled by a turn\nof fortune.\n\u2018\u2018Margin calls occasionally cause a\n\u25a0udden dumping of mint stamps held\nby speculators who need ready cash.\nThis condition has caused a further\nsoftening of prices on recent United\nStates postage issues.\n\u2018\u2018It is possible now to buy huge\nquantities of current and near-current\nUnited States airmails at substantial\ndiscounts from face values.\n\"These are reaching the market\nfrom banks and stamp brokers who\nhave lent money on the accumula\ntions, only to have the borrowers de\nfault on their interest and principal\npayments.\n\"This condition has not yet been\nreflected in price lists of retail and\nwholesale dealers, but they make no\nsecret of the fact that their orders\nhave fallen off sharply.\n\"Auction dealers continue to be\nflooded with sale material and dis\nappointing prices are realized for re\ncent issue*. Better grade material,\nIssued before 1932, is relatively firm,\nhowever.\n\"The stamp market Is more sensi\ntive in the East than in the Middle\nWest. Eastern markets are the first\nto reflect price changes.\n\"In a period of rising prices, New\nYork auctions will show better real\nizations than elsewhere, but when quo\ntations are falling, auction sales out\nside New York City are likely to\nShow firmer prices.\n\"The reason is that there are no\nNation-wide distribution of daily re\nports on stamp market conditions, as\nthere is for stock prices.\n\"Western collectors do not realize\nuntil several weeks too late that they\nhave bid higher than conditions jus\ntify In a period of declining values.\u201d\n\nThe International Philatelic Week\nExhibition of the Central Federation\nof Stamp Clubs will be held at the\nMedinah Club, 505 North Michigan\navenue, Chicago, Thursday to Sat\nurday, November 18 to 20, inclusive.\nFred W. Peters and Paul Zaring are\nin charge of arrangements.\nAt the Philippine trade commis\naioner's office, Barr Building, four dif\nferent types of 2-centavo envelopes\nand three 4-centavo, recently re\nh ceived from Manila, are available.\nAlso, two official postal cards, book\nlets of 2-centavo stamps, 2-centavo\nO. B. overprints and new stocks of\nbroken sets of 1935 and 1936 Com\nmonwealth and airmail overprints.\nDavid H. Davenport, writing in Me\nkeel's Weekly Stamp News, says: \"With\nthe stamp program for 1937 completed,\npostal officials are turning their at\ntention once more to the delayed revi\nsion of the regular series, and from a\nreliable source comes the information\nthat the first of this group will prob\nably appear in January. If collectors\nhave experienced difficulty keeping\npace with the 11 commemoratives, two\nairmails and one souvenir pane already\nreleased this year, and with four more\ncommemoratives announced, they\nshould prepare themselves for a shock\nduring the coming year, especially if\nthe new current series progresses to\nthe release of the higher values.\u201d\n\u00abs... __\nGuatemala will issue on November\n15 a miniature sheet of four stamps\nIn commemoration of the sesquicen\ntennial of the adoption of the Consti\nbutton of the United States. The de\nalgns will include portraits of Lincoln\nand Franklin D. Roosevelt, a map of\nthe three Americas and, probably, the\nPan-American Union Building in\nWashington. Colors specified are light\nand dark blue and dark brown. The\nedition will be 100,000 and face value\n38 cents, yielding a profit of approxi\nmately $35,000 to the Guatemalan gov\nernment.\nPortugal announces another stamp\nfor the Geographical Society of Lis\nban\u2014le, lilac and red, type F-5.\nThe late Maj. Frank R. Sweet of\nAttleboro, Mass., left a philatelic\nestate appraised at $250,000.\nAlice Woodruff finds that great men\nare commemorated in precancels from\nthe following towns: Columbus, De\nSoto, Hudson, La Salle. Joliet, Mar\nquette, Raleigh, Fremont, Boone,\nHamilton, Greeley. Garrison, Thoreau,\nBurbank, Fulton, Bell, Carnegie,\nGladstone. Newton. La Grange, Dumas,\nBarnum, Gilbert and Stanley.\nBy combining two stamps in each\ncase. Miss Woodruff gets: Alice Brady,\nJeannette McDonald, Gary Cooper,\nShirley Temple, Wayne king and\nMorton Downey.\nHerman Boeorselski, well known in\nWashington philatelic circles, has re\nturned from his holiday in New\nfoundland. He made ample use of his\nopportunity to enlarge his already\ncomprehensive collection of British\nNorth America.\nA new, revised and greatly en\nlarged edition of \"Portrait Stamps.\u201d\nby Fredrik Arsenius, is announced by\nOlofsson Bros.\u2019 Printing House. Stock\nholm. Sweden. The text is in English\nand there are 800 illustrations.\nThe first issue of Avocations, pub\nlished by Harry L. Lindquist, has been\nreceived. It contains a considerable\nquantity of philatelic news, also arti\ncles on \"Things That Interest Me,\u201d by\nH. Bedford-Jones. and \"Miniature\nSheets of Stamps,\u201d by Frank L. Wil\nson.\nExtension of the clipper ship air\nmail service to New Zealand is ru\nmored, but no official announcement\nis as yet at hand.'\nThe 1937 Tuberculosis Christmas\nSeals will show a \u201cJolly old English\nnight watchman with his lantern and\nbell.\u201d\nFunds to finance the first centennial i\nof national independence will be\nsought by the Dominican Republic\ngovernment through a so-called \u201cCen\ni tenary Issue\u201d of stamps obligatory\non all first-class mail. The celebra\ntion is scheduled for 1944.\nElmer C. Pratt, philatelic editor of\nthe Camden Courier Post, writes:\n\"The new Constitution stamp is a\nfine example of just what our Wash\nington engravers can do with a stamp\nissue if given the time and the ma\nterial to work with.\u201d\nIn the first number of the bulletin\nof the Souvenir Issue Association, Dr.\nCharles H. Evans, president, says:\n\"Honest criticism tends to temper our\nprogress into new fields of stamp col\nlecting, as well as to keep various\ngovernments conscious of their duty\nto the real stamp collector.\u201d\nThe Woodbridge Stamp Club, meet\ning at 2010 Rhode Island avenue\nnortheast, Monday evening, elected\nofficers as follows: Edward Miller,\npresident; Thomas E. Stackhouse, vice\npresident; Wes. M. Tryon, secretary\ntreasurer. David Thompson, a Junior\nmember, exhibited and described re\ncent commemoratives of France, and\nMiss Jean Tryon recited a phila\ntelic poem. It was voted to take an\nactive part in the program for Na\ntional Stamp week. Speakers at the\nnext meeting, Monday evening, Octo\nber 25, will be Frederick J. Roy,\nHoward A. Peterson and Lewis Scott.\nA. E. Geldhof, stamp editor of the\nChicago Herald-Examiner, calls at\ntention to the fact that the figure to\nbe represented on the Hawaiian ter\nritorial issue is not really that of King\nKamehameha. Instead, the model was\n\u201ca handsome young Hawaiian named\nKaopuiki.\u201d An authentic portrait of\nthe famous South Seas Napoleon \"was\nonce used on a Hawaiian revenue\nstamp and could easily have been re\nproduced for the new commemora\ntive.\u201d\nMrs. Grace L. Mac Knight, editor of\nthe Washington Collectors\u2019 Club bul\nletin, says: \u201cThere can be no ques\ntion but what more and more people\nare becoming first-day cover collec\ntors.\" She cites 281,478 mailings of\nthe Constitution stamp as compared\nwith 50,000 of the Vermont sesqui\ncentennial commemorative 10 years\nago.\nMore than 5,000,000 copies of the\nS. P. A. 10-cent Parks miniature\nsheets were printed, but the Post\nOffice Department probably will not\nannounce final sales figures for nearly\na month. The labels were taken off\nthe Philatelic Agency list on Monday\nand it was understood that accumu\nlated orders, dating back two or three\nweeks, then were on hand. Actual\nprinting orders to the Bureau of En\ngraving and Printing have been re\nported as exactly 5,000,000. Some ad\nditional sheets may have been run off\nto provide against inevitable waste.\nWhen the government of Burma an\nnounced a competition for designs for\na premier series of stamps a few weeks\nago. it warned artists not to picture a\npagoda in their drawings. The Bur\nmans are Buddhists and pagodas are\nsacred buildings. It was considered\nsacriligious to risk cancellations of\nany such shrines. Hence the decision\nof the authorities to avoid trouble.\nThere are 39 figures in the vignette\nof the 3-cent Constitution stamp. \u201cA\nperson of average eyesight.\u201d says the\nPhiladelphia Inquirer, \u201crequires a\nstrong lens to discern the founding\nfathers.\u201d\nDue to revision of postal rates.\nPrance has brought out a 65c, \u201cpeace\u201d\ntype, stamp in blue and retired the\nordinary 45c value.\nThe first Italian Empire stamps are\nscheduled for release on October 28.\nFinal figures on the King Constan\ntine mourning stamps of Greece are\nannounced as: 3d, 2,059,761 copies, and\n8d, 656,976 copies.\nWeekly Philatelic Gossip reports:\n\u201cIn the French zone of British Moroc\nco, Great Britain has turned over to\nFrench postal authorities the handling\nof all mails out of Casablanca, Marra\nkesh. Mazagan and Saffi, and in a\nfew months Fez and Rabat also will be\nclosed. This move on the part of the\nBritish government comes as part of\nthe terms of a new Anglo-French\ntreaty and in no way affects British\noffices at Larrache and Tetuan or at\nTangier in the international zone. It\nis possible that by the end of 1937\nthe British postal system will cease to\nfunction in all parts of Morocco. This\nwill end a period of 80 years of such\nmail supervision.\u201d\nStamp meetings for the week are\nlisted as follows:\nMonday evening at 7:30. Washing\nton Stamp Club of the Air from Sta\ntion WOL. Mr. Kunze will continue\nhis discussion of history and stamps.\nMonday evening at 8. Washington\nAir Mail Society, Hotel Lafayette, Six\nteenth street.\nTuesday evening at 8, Washington\nCollectors' Club. Branch 5. Society\nof Philatelic Americans, Thomson\nSchool, Twelfth street. Auction, bourse,\nexhibition and program.\nTuesday evening at 8, Viking\u2019s Crew\nNo. 8, American Naval Cancellation\nSociety, home of Mrs. Fred D. Riggles,\n35 Rhode Island avenue, northwest.\nWednesday evening at 6:45, Wash\nington Federation of Junior Stamp\nCollectors, Hotel Carlton, Sixteenth\nstreet. Program and exhibition, a\nshort talk by Mr. Kunze, stamp con\ntest, award of prizes for annual show.\nWednesday evening at 8, Washing\nton Philatelic Society, Hotel Carlton.\nMovies of the coronation of King\nGeorge VI, tour of the Shakespeare\ncountry and the Thames Valley, ex\nhibition of stamps and covers of five\nreigns and piano recital by Miss Chris\ntine Kelley, child artist, pupil of Mme.\nLouise Coutinho.\nSaturday afternoon at 1 Philatelic\nLuncheon Group, Hotel Harrington,\nEleventh street.\nAll meetings are open to the pub\nlic and collectors are assured of cor\ndial welcome.\nOUTLOOK BRIGHT\nFOR DAIRY FARMER\nButter and Cheese Prices Gain,\nWhile Live Stock Feed Costs\nShow Declines.\nEy the Associated Press.\nThings look bright for the dairy\nfarmer this Winter, the Agriculture\nDepartment said yesterday, with but\nter and cheese prices Increasing and\nlive stock feed costs declining.\nGovernment charts showed butter\nand cheese prices had climbed re\ncently to the highest point of the year.\nEconomists said this increase would\ncontinue, with prices this Winter av\neraging the highest since 1929-30.\nButterfat prices Increased 8 per cent\nfrom mid-June to mid-September, the\neconomists said, while feed costs de\nclined 26 per cent. The large com\ncrop is expected to result in further\nfeed cost reductions.\nAnother favorable factor, the econo\nmists said, was a heavy movement\nof dairy products from storage re\ncently. The out-of-storage movement\nof butter during September was largest\nsince 1932 and stocks on October 1\nwere below the average of recent years.\n_STAMPS. _\nSTAMPS\u2014COINS\u2014AUTnr.\u00bbApn<t\nBoasht and Sold\n,,.v HOBBY SHOP\nTIB 17th St. N.W._Dlmtrlct 1272\nFranc* Constitution Stomp 12c\nBcott'a 1938 Standard Catalos _ _S3 00\nNow Modern Album. Ready Oct. 15 \"si 00\n1838 U. S. Catalos. Oct. 25_ S3 00\nCULLEN'S 8TAMP SHOP\np2\u00bb G St., N.W. _ MET. 8817\nUYENO\u2019S STAMP SHOP\n1205 Penn. Aye. N.W._Met. 9014\nWHITNEY\u2019S STAMP MART\n402 12th St. N.W._Met._6593_\nNATIONAL STAMP MART\n1317 F St N.W,. Km. 411, Plat. 8217\nSTAMP ALBUMS\nStack Boeks. Catalasoea. New Sets. Slnrle\ntamPi Philatelic Sapnllea. Call and ace\naae. I also BUY Collections.\nHARRY B. MASON, 918 F N.W,\nFARLEY\nSinglet, Complete_$2.39\nBlocks of 4_$9.39\nFidelity Stamp Store\n420 Eve. Star Bldg. Nat. 6346\n1\nAustrian Air Post Novelty\nThis interesting cover, reproduced by courtesy of Dr. Emil\nFerdinand Hirschberger, commemorates an important aviation\nmeet held at Vienna recently. With two airmail stamps and\nthree cachets, it is, in effect, a fragment of history\u2014fascinating\nfor its philatelic value and as an index of aeronautic progress.\n\u2014Star Staff Photo.\nLi\nBuyers Hold Back Until\nWholesale Staple Trend\nIs Clarified.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, October 16.\u2014Until\nwholesale commodity prices give some\nindication of having found their bot\ntom, there is little prospect that buy\ners can be induced to step up their\npurchasing programs and provide in\ndustry with the means of expanding\noperations. Moody's price index of\n15 sensitive commodities has cut not\nonly through the October, 1936, level,\nbut through that of October, 1935, as\nwell, the decline from the April peak\nbeing 25 per cent. The bumper cot\nton crop forecast late last week led\ntextile buyers to press harder for con\ncessions on cotton fabrics. Automotive\nconcerns, as they go into production\non 1938 cars, are buying steel on a\n30-day basis instead of several months\nahead. Foreign steel buyers are no\nlonger offering premiums for steel, but\nasking concessions and getting them.\nAuto Production Soars.\nThe automobile industry has pushed\nits output up to 72,000 cars a week,\nwithout the aid of Ford, which has\nbeen closed for three weeks. Now\nthat Ford is resuming activity, the in\ndustry will begin to get its showtime\nstride. October is counted on to show\na 50 per cent increase over last year's\noutput. September was only 20 per\ncent ahead.\nFord's announcement this week of\na $40,000,000 expansion program draws\nattention to the extensive construction\nprojects undertaken by the motor in\ndustry in preparation for next year\u2019s\noutput. Ford\u2019s program is intended\nto increase the company\u2019s self-suf\nficiency and will include the world's\nlargest blast furnace, estimated to cost\nabout $4,500,000. Packard announced\na $13,000,000 program late in Septem\nber. Buick has spent $10,000,000. And\nthis week's construction contracts con\ntain a plant, costing $6,500,000, for the\nCadillac-La Salle division of General\nMotors.\nSteel Firms Disappointed.\nSteel companies were a bit disap\npointed to find the motor manufac\nturers buying so sparingly, but as\nthere is little danger of price advances\nin steel, and some uncertainty as to\nhow the public will take to the higher\npriced cars of 1938, the automo\nbile men\u2019s caution is not surprising.\nThough steel prices are well above\nthe 1929 level and have not followed\nother prices down recently, steel mills\nare reported to have taken a firm\nstand against concessions, at least to\ndomestic buyers. To sustain their\nposition, mills are expected to post\nfirst-quarter prices shortly, reaffirming\nthose now' prevailing.\nAdvances of almost per cent in\nrents and clothing, and of 1.2 per\ncent in coal prices, pushed the wage\nearner's cost of living in September\nslightly ahead of the preceding month.\nCompared with last year, living costs\nare up 4.1 per cent; compared with\nthe low in 1933, they are up 24.7 per\ncent, but compared with 1929, they\nare still down 11.6 per cent.\nI r\u00abrvnr\u00bbrtn a nri/vAT I\nwiu v/itftiivn\nREPORTS\nTRENDS AND PROSPECTS OF\nLEADING ORGANIZATIONS.\nNEW YORK, October 16\u2014The\nfollowing is today's summary of cor\nporation news prepared by Standard\nStatistics Co., Inc., New York:\nMesta Machine Co. President\nstated that orders of company are\ncoming in at a normal rate and un\nfilled orders still are from $20,000,000\nto $21,000,000. Operations of Mesta\nare at capacity, he added, and there\nIs enough business on hand and in\nprospect to assure 100 per cent oper\nations throughout 1938. New con\nstruction work to expand plant is\nabout 90 per cent completed.\nUnderwood-EUiott-Fisher Co.\u2014Com\nmon share earnings, nine months\nended September 30, were $4.62,\nagainst $2.76.\nStandard Oil Co. of New Jersey\u2014\nCompany reduced spot tank-car price\nof United States motor gasoline U\ncent a gallon at all refineries and\nterminals.\nBaldwin Locomotive Works\u2014Con\nsolidated bookings in September to\ntaled $1,673,241, against $2,532,734 in\nSeptember. 1936. In nine months to\ntal was $27,905,527, against $23,902,\n050. Consolidated shipments in Sep\ntember totaled $2,397,298, against\n$1,719,434 in September, 1936. In\nnine months total was $29,190,436,\nagainst $16,833,497. Unfilled orders\nas of September 30, 1937, totaled $29,\n622,017, against $30,531,416 on Janu\nary, 1, 1937, and $13,781,459 on Sep\ntember 30, 1936. All figures Include\nMidvale Co. and are without inter\ncompany eliminations.\nLehigh Valley Railroad\u2014Company\nhas cash on hand to meet the inter\nest due November 1, 1937, amounting\nto $1,563,716 on its general consoli\ndated mortgage bonds.\nAmerican Rolling Mill Co.\u2014Com\npany appropriated $2,000,000 to im\nprove the plant at Middletown, Ohio.\nTruscon Steel Co.\u2014Common share\nearnings, nine months ended Septem\nber 30, were 37 cents, against 60\ncents.\n\nBand Concerts.\n/CONCERTS by the United States\nSoldiers\u2019 Home Band Orchestra,\nStanley Hall, 5:30 o\u2019clock. John S.\nM. Zimmermann, bandmaster; Anton\nPointner, assistant.\nTUESDAY. 6:30 P.M.\nMarch. \u201cBay State Commandery,\u201d Burrell\nOverture. \u201cAmerican Festival\u2019\u2019_Meaner\nEntr\u2019acte\u2014\n(a) \u201cAir de Ballet\" _Victor Herbert\n(b) \u201cAdagio Cantablle\"..Richard Straui\nScenes from the opera \u201cThe Bartered\nBride\" _ Smetana\nPopular numbers, \u201cAll Muddled Up.\u201d\nWenrleh\n\u201cAn Armchair With an Armful of You,\u201d\nSilver\nWaltz suite. \u201cAbandon\" (Oanz verlassen).\nWaldteufel\nFinale, \u201cChtng Chons\"... -Roberts\n\u201cThe Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nTHURSDAY, 6:30 P.M.\nMarch. \u201cSwedish Wedding March.\u201d\nSoederman\nOverture, \u201cBritantcus\" Scassola\nOriental suite. \u201cFrom India\" Pony\n1. \u201cThe Bayaderes.\" 2. \u201cBy the Ganges.\"\n3. \"The Almas.\u201d 4. \u201cOriental Patrol.\"\nMelange, \"America Forever\" Tobani\nPopular numbers, \"Alone in the Rain.\u201d\nDougherty\n\u201cAdorable\" Wynburne\nWaltz suite. \"The Aero Travelers.\u201d Weiss\nFinale \"The Caroltonlan\" Boehnlein\n'The Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nSATURDAY. 6:30 P.M.\nMarch. \u201cBonnie Blues\u201d __ Chy^hbers\nOverture. \"Bohemian Life\u201d _ .Berggfiholtz\nSuite Oriental. \u201cArabian Nights/\u2019\nOruanwald\n1. \u201cDanse des Odalisques.\u201d 2. \u2019\u2022Sind\nbad.\u201d 3. \u201cA Love Duet.\u201d 4. \u201cQhasl.\u201d\nScenes from the opera, \u201cAlda\" (request),\nVerdi\nPopular numbers, \u201cAuf Wledersehen, My\nDear\" _ Aser\n\"At Sundown\u201d (request)._Donaldson\nValsette. \u2019\u2019Antoinette'7 .....-..Rosner\nk\nCommodity Price\nChanges for Week\nBY A. A. PATTON,\nAssociated Press Statistician.\nNEW YORK, October 16.\u2014Com\nmodity prices rallied moderately this\nweek, with upturns in farm staples\nmore than offsetting continued weak\nness in Industrial items.\nFoods, live stock and agricultural\nproducts were Included among gain\ners; textiles, non-ferrous metals and\nother industrial commodities declined.\nQuotations hit a new low for tl\\e\nyear on Monday, but, despite crum\nbling stock prices, recovered.\nThe Associated Press weighted index\nof 35 important wholesale staple spot\nprices rose to 83.00 per cent of the\n1926 average, from 82.91 a week ago\nand compared with 81.29 last year.\nCotton Recovers Briskly.\nCotton was bid up briskly. Some\nquarters said the upturn was in part\na rebound from the drastic slump of\nlast week. Demand for finished goods\nalso picked up, pushing consumption\nabove production for the first time\nsince last July. Then, too, the huge\ncrop was believed to have brought\noutput control nearer.\nGrains were mixed; wheat and oats\nrising fractions, corn and rye slip\nping.\nAfter falling back somewhat in the\npast month, live stock took the up\nward path this week. Cattle and lambs\nboth improved. A shortage of ani\nmals was reported in most markets.\nWith eggs and lard firm, items en\ntering the market basket nudged\nahead slightly despite a dip in cocoa\nthat followed reports of a larger crop\nabroad.\nTextiles Slump Again.\nTextiles slumped for the eleventh\nconsecutive time to new lows for the\nyear. Oversupply continued to burden\nmany manufacturers and dealers. A\nreaction in wool more than balanced\na minor upswing in silk. The latter\nstemmed principally from expected\ncurtailment of Japanese shipments.\nTin, lead and zinc were among\nthe weakest non-ferrous metals. Heavy\ninventories and slack demand hit this\ngroup, with curtailed production pro\ngrams announced by several important\ncompanies.\nSteel scrap led the decline among\nindustrial staples, followed by rub\nber. bituminous coal and turpentine.\nThe index, with its components\nbased on 1926 as 100, compared as\nfollows:\nn. Oct 15. Pv. wk. Yr ago.\n\u202215 commodities 83.00 83.Hi 81 20\nIndustrial yo.17 \u00bbo>y 83 72\nfood H8.sn HS4I 72.76\nLive stock -101) 60 108.76 78 73\nAgriculture _ 78.58 77 45 1)1 oi\nTextile -*58 48 58 -8 72 33\nNon-fer. metal _ 84.76 86.53 68.34\n\u2022New iy.37 low.\nPROFITS OF BUDD\nMANUFACTURING UP\n\n$107,465 Net in Quarter Compares\nWith $547,400 Loss in Same\n1936 Period.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nPHILADELPHIA, October IS.\u2014The\nEdward G. Budd Manuacturing Co.\ntoday reported a net profit of $107,\n465 for the third quarter of the year\nafter deducting all charges, including\ninterest, depreciation and taxes, but\nnot Including any provision for the\nFederal undistributed profits tax.\nThis compares with a net loss of\n$547,400 In the third quarter of 1936.\nEarnings for the first nine months\nof this year were $1,198,329. against\nan operating profit of $138,434 for\nthe first nine months of last year.\nThe Budd Wheel Co. reported a\nprofit of $75,055 for the third quarter\nof the current year after deducting\nall charges, including depreciation,\ninterest and normal taxes, but not In\ncluding any provision for the Federal\nundistributed profits tax.\nThis compares with a profit of\n$140,035 for the third quarter of 1936.\nEarnings for the first nine months of\nthis year were $596,015. equal to 58\ncents a share after providing for cur\nrent preferred dividend on the 965,\n258 shares of outstanding common\nstock. This compares with earnings\nof $658,728 for the first nine months\nof the previous year, equal to 64\ncents per share on the 965,258 shares\nof common stock.\nESB I\nFactory Output Also Sags\nas Inventories Remain\nat High Levels.\nSpecial Dispatch to ThE Star.\nNEW YORK, October 16.\u2014In its\nweekly summary of the general busi\nness situation the Standard Statistics\nCo. of New York, currently comments\nas follows:\n\u201cRecent developments have done\nlittle to clarify the business outlook\nor to remove the general feeling of\nuneasiness which has developed over\nthe past month or two. Production in\na number of industries, particularly in\nthe heavier lines, is continuing to de\ncline. Basic raw material prices show\nno signs of reversing their downward\ntrend, and further weakness in security\nprices is continuing to depress senti\nment.\n\u2018The failure of new' orders to de\nvelop in many lines has, of course,\nbeen the chief reason for the decline\nin operating schedules. Until recently,\nmany manufacturers were able to\nmaintain operations at high rates be\ncause of heavy order backlogs built\nup early this year. Not only has new\nbusiness failed to improve, but demand\nhas declined further, as manufacturers\nhave restricted purchases to a hand-to\nmouth basis because of falling security\nand commodity prices.\n\u201cIt is now generally recognized that\nbusiness is paying the penalty of spec\nulative excesses late last year and\nearly in 1937. Inventories were built\nup considerably above normal as a pro\ntection against higher prices and\nthreatened labor troubles. Although\ninventories have been steadily reduced\nsince the peak was reached last Spring,\nthey are still generally heavy. More\nover, there is no incentive to follow\nother than a conservative buying pro\ngram so long as commodity prices are\ndeclining and the labor situation is\nrelatively quiet.\n\u201cIt is difficult to determine when\nthe present deflationary movement\nwill have run its course. One encour\naging development is that the distri\nbution of goods, as measured by retail\ntrade figures, is being well maintained,\nand an active Fall season would sug\ngest that business will enter the new\nyear in a relatively healthy inventory\nposition. Furthermore, a number of\nlines, 6uch as textiles, are adjusting\ntheir schedules as rapidly as possible\nto the lower demand, in order to pre\nvent supplies from backing up into the\nhands of the primary producers.\u201d\nWOOL MARKET QUIET,\nPRICES EASE UNEVENLY\nBy the Associated Press.\nBOSTON, October 16 (United\nStates Department of Agriculture).\u2014\nThe wool market during the past\nweek was quiet, except for scattered j\ntrading in odd lots at prices irreg-1\nularly lower than quotations on the\nbulk of holdings.\nLarge holders made no attempt to\nsell because of widespread indiffer\nence of buyers. Quotations were nom\ninally based upon prices at which\nsizable quantities were available in\nhouses offering wools.\nGraded combing Ohio fleeces were\nquoted at 38-40 cents in the grease\nfor fine delaine, 39-40 cents for sta\nble combing length half bloods, 40-42\ncents for three-eighths and 38-40\nfor quarter bloods.\nFEDERAL EGG BUYING\nNEAR $285,000 MARK\nBr the Associated Press.\nThe Federal Government spent\nabout $285,000 this week buying\n1,265,040 dozesn eggs, officials said\nyesterday, in an effort to improve\nprices received by farmers.\nThe Agricultural Adjustment Ad\nministration said 105 carloads of eggs\nhad been purchased throughout the\nUnited States, chiefly at storage cen\nters, at an average price of about 22 *2\ncents a dozen.\nThe eggs will be turned over to State\nagencies for free distribution to relief\nclients.\nAUTO SHOW\nPUZZLE CONTEST\nTHIS IS PUZZLE NO. 13.\nCASTE Mental appearance j\nCALF Pertaining to focus j\nSEED Thick and compact j\nCRANE To retract I\nROAN A water wheel f\nREPLV Before the usual time\nROU6E A path or track 1\nAdd a letter to each word shown in the left-hand column and rearrange\nthe letters to spell a word for which the definition is given. Insert the new\nword below the definition and place the added letter to the last column\nopposite the new word. If the puzzle is solved correctly, the added letters will\nspell the trade name of one of the twenty-two (22) automobiles shown in the\nlist below, to be exhibited at the Eighteenth Annual Automobile Show of\nWashington, D. C., from October 30 to November 6, 1937, inclusive, at the\nAutomotive Exhibit Hall, 1242 Twenty-fourth street northwest, between M\nand N streets, under the auspices of the Washington Automotive Trade\nAssociation, which, with the co-operation of The Star, is conducting this\ncontest.\nBUICK FORD NASH PONTIAC\nCADILLAC GRAHAM OLDSMOBILE STUDEBAKER\nCHEVROLET HUDSON pirTtARn TERRAPLANE\nCHRYSLER HUPMOBILE PACKARD_ TERRAPLANE\nDE SOTO LA SALLE PIERCE-ARROW WILLYS\nDODGE LINCOLN PLYMOUTH ZEPHYR\nThe first pumle appeared on October 5, 1937. A different one will\nappear each day until October 26, 1937. The puzzles which have appeared prior\nto this one may be studied from the files in the business office of The Star.\nSolve each puzzle, and not earlier than October 26, 1937, but not later\nthan midnight, October 27, 1937, send all of the solutions with a reason of\nnot more than twenty (20) words \u201cAs to Why an Automobile Show Should\nBe Held In Washington, D. C\u201e to the Washington Automotive Trade\nAssociation, 1427 I street northwest, Washington, D. C.\nIt is not necessary to send in the actual puzzles, but it is compulsory\nthat the entries show the new words. The new words will not be given out\nor published, and no entries will be returned.\nOfficials of the Washington Automotive Trade Association, whose deci\nsions will be final, will act as Judges, and, based on correctness, neatness\nand manner in which the solutions are submitted, as well as the reason for\nholding an Annual Automobile Show, will award prizes totaling (100 and 100\ntickets to the Automobile Show, as follows: First prize, (50 and 12 tickets;\nsecond prize, (25 and 8 tickets; third prize, (10 and 6 tickets; fourth prize,\n(5 and 4 tickets; 10 prizes of (1 each and 2 tickets and 25 prizes of 2 tickets\neach. In case of ties duplicate prizes will be awarded.\nWinners will be announced in the Automobile Show Section of The\nSunday Star on October 81, 1937. Questions should be addressed to Wash\nington Automotive Trade Association, 1427 I street northwest, Washing\nton, D. C.\nI A\nFOOD PURCHASE PRICES\nFOR HOTELS INCREASE\nSpecial Dlipatch to Tho Star.\nNEW YORK. October 16.\u2014Septem\nber hotel food purchase prices In\ncreased 3.79 per cent over August,\n1937, price levels, according to the\nlatest Grinstead hotel food price index\ncompiled monthly by R. M. Grinstead\nSc Co., Inc.\nThe September index was 129.44, as\ncompared with 119.42 in September of\na year ago, being an Increase of 8.39\nper cent this September over last\nSeptember.\nAll food co6t groups except groceries\nadvanced over August levels, the\ngreatest increases being shown on\nfresh salads and vegetables. Meat\ncost prices are now 22.65 per cent\nhigher than in last September.\nPoultry in September was 5.97 per\ncent higher than last September; fish,\n3.02 per cent higher; vegetables, 0.80\nper cent higher; fruit, 7.47 per cent\nhigher, and groceries, 1.17 per cent\nhigher. Salads are now 4.24 per cent\nlower than a year ago and dairy prod\nucts are down 7.72 per cent.\nMACHINERY EXPORTS\nWELL ABOVE YEAR AGO\nEy the Associated Press.\nAugust machinery exports totaled\n$21,692,000. the Commerce Depart\nment reports, an increase of 78 per\ncent over the same month a year ago.\nFor the first eight months of this\nyear these exports totaled $162,\n675,000, an increase of 46 per cent\nover the total for the entire year of\n1938.\nMONROE CALCULATING\nREVEALS SALES JUMP\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, October 16.\u2014The\nMonroe Calculating Machine Co. re\nports sales for the quarter ending\nSeptember 30 were the best in the\ncompany's history and were 44 per\ncent ahead of the same period in\n1936. Business for 1937 to date ex\nceeds the total for the same period in\n1936 by 17 per ecnt.\nFOUND.\nSUIT CASE\u2014Oct. 12, S:15 c m. Lady's\napparel. Edward J. Wright. 014 Mass.\nave. n.w.\nLOST.\nBILLFOLD, brown, containing about\nrash, auto license and other identifying\npapers. Keep money, return billfold and\npapers to Capt. Schlatter, Officers' Club,\nBolling Field._\nBUICK WOOD WHEEL, tire, tube and\nrim. and Part of rear axle: very liberal\nreward offered. Wade's Auto Service, 518\nloth st, n.e. Lincoln 7725._\nDIAMOND EARRING, spiral setting. Sun.,\nbet. 3-5 p.m.. vie. Cn. Ch. bus to 14th and\nEuclid-11 th to G to Brookland. 550 reward.\nClev. 6331._\nDIAMOND-SAPPHIRE bow knot pin. Re\nward. 614 Brighton Hotel, Potomac 4851.\n16*\nDOG. English setter, black and white bird\ndog. named \"Bert.\" Lost Sunday from the\nZantzinger farm. n**ar Oak Grove. Prince\nGeorges\u2019 County. Md. Liberal reward.\nMarlboro 24-F-21. National 9593._\nENVELOPE. October 12. near Chevy Chase\nCircle, in street, shop or bus, bank enve\nlope. containing securities tnot trans\nferable; and letter, reward. Box 24